<TITLE> "Verdict cannot go against us" </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 31 (bdnews24.com)  The Election Commission says the ruling on re-demarcation of parliamentary constituencies, set for Sunday (Nov 2), "cannot go against us". The week-long hearing on three separate writ petitions challenging the EC's gazette on demarcation of 300 parliamentary constituencieswhich redrew the boundaries of 133 seatsconcluded in the High Court on Thursday. The commission on the same day asked the Appellate Division to vacate the HC stay order on the gazette. The stay order, given on the back of the petitions, is the main obstacle to announcing the schedule for elections. The HC's verdict and the hearing on the EC's appeal are both due on Sunday. Commissioner Muhammad Sohul Hussain told bdnews24.com that re-demarcation is a constitutional obligation for the Election Commission, and added: "In this case the verdict cannot go against us." "If the verdict goes against us, we will appeal." The top polls officials briefed the chief adviser on Thursday of all the circumstances leading to the Election Commission delaying its announcement of the polls schedule that had been set for Nov. 2. Chief election commissioner ATM Shamsul Huda, with fellow commissioners Sohul Hussain and M Sakhawat Hossain, filled the CA in on the state of the legal tussle. Sohul told bdnews24.com: "The election schedule cannot be announced before settlement of these issues. We hope the verdict will go in our favour. The schedule for national and upazila elections will be announced as soon as possible after getting the verdict." He said the ninth parliamentary elections would be held under the redrawn boundaries of the constituencies. Before going to meeting, CEC Shamsul Huda had also told journalists, "The EC has a constitutional obligation to redraw boundaries of constituencies." Asked when the schedule may be announced, Sohul said, "The election schedule will be announced as soon as possible. If it is done by November 7 we will have enough time in hand." He pointed out that the schedule for the last national election was announced 32 days before the polls. The commissioner said the schedules for the Dec 18 general election, and for upazila polls on Dec 24 and 28, will be announced on the same day. bdnews24.
